6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Bybit uses traditional 8-hour funding intervals with TWAP-based rate calculations, allowing positions to build larger imbalances before settlement. Paradex implements hourly funding on StarkNet, providing more frequent rebalancing but requiring constant monitoring. Bybit's longer intervals suit swing arbitrage strategies, while Paradex's hourly settlements favor scalping approaches. Both exchanges use similar premium-index methodologies but Paradex benefits from lower gas costs on L2."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate opportunities?","answer":"Bybit typically provides more stable arbitrage opportunities due to deeper liquidity and established market making. Paradex's hourly settlements can create more frequent but smaller arbitrage windows."},{"question":"How do funding calculations differ between the exchanges?","answer":"Both use premium-index methodologies, but Bybit calculates over 8-hour periods while Paradex settles hourly. Paradex's frequent settlements reduce position risk but require more active management."},{"question":"What are the main risks for arbitrageurs on each platform?","answer":"Bybit poses counterparty risk as a CEX but offers stable infrastructure. Paradex eliminates custody risk but faces smart contract risks and potential StarkNet network issues."},{"question":"Which platform is better for institutional arbitrage strategies?","answer":"Bybit currently serves institutions better with proven liquidity and API stability. Paradex shows promise for institutions requiring self-custody but lacks sufficient market depth for large strategies."}]}]
